<subSubSection id="C32F65126B7DFFD24096E28AFB5F493C" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B8A36996B7DFFD24096E28AFEA94B5C" blockId="3.[151,1436,151,818]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis id="B941EA8B6B7DFFD24096E28AFECA4ABF" bold="true" box="[198,319,151,177]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">Remarks.</emphasis>
The present trichodinid species is mainly characterized by possessing a slender blade with Sshaped anterior hooked blade surface. Based on the overall shape of the adhesive disc, the new species differs significantly from other known trichodinid species and only shows some resemblance to 
<taxonomicName id="4C354D1A6B7DFFD24492E2F5FEEA4B24" authority="Chen, 1963" authorityName="Chen" authorityYear="1963" class="Oligohymenophorea" family="Trichodinidae" genus="Trichodina" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Peritrichida" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="nobilis">
<emphasis id="B941EA8B6B7DFFD24492E2F5FA694B0F" box="[1218,1436,232,257]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">Trichodina nobilis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFA44B686B7DFFD240C7E30DFEEA4B24" author="Chen, Q. - L." box="[151,287,272,298]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" pagination="197 - 225" refId="ref5038" refString="Chen, Q. - L. (1963) Studies on ecotoparasitic trichodinids from fresh-water fish, tadpole and crustacean in China. Acta Hydrobiologica Sinnica, 2, 197 - 225 (in Chinese with English summary)." type="journal article" year="1963">Chen, 1963</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFA44B686B7DFFD24161E30DFE354B24" author="Chen, Q. - L." box="[305,448,272,298]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" refId="ref5003" refString="Chen, Q. - L. (1973) Illustrations of fish pathogens in Hubei province. (In Chinese). Scicnce Publ. House, Peking, China, 329 pp." type="book" year="1973">Chen, 1973</bibRefCitation>
). However, these two species also show some obvious differences (
<figureCitation id="130E2A1C6B7DFFD244B5E30DFA844B24" box="[1253,1393,272,298]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[151,255,1158,1182]" captionTargetBox="[166,1426,315,1145]" captionTargetId="figure-403@7.[166,1426,314,1145]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 3. Diagrammatic drawing of the denticles of Trichodina spp. A–B. Trichodina subtilihamata sp. nov.; C: Trichodina uniforma Van As &amp; Basson, 1989; D: Trichodina nigra Lom, 1960; E–F: Trichodina kazubski Van As &amp; Basson, 1989; G–H: Trichodina mutabilis Kazubski &amp; Migala, 1968." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5097611" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5097611/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">Figs. 3A, B</figureCitation>
) as discussed below.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8A36996B7DFFD24097E37DFEBD4814" blockId="3.[151,1436,151,818]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">
In terms of the morphometric data in both trichodinids, 
<taxonomicName id="4C354D1A6B7DFFD24301E37DFBBF4B74" authority="Chen, 1963" authorityName="Chen" authorityYear="1963" box="[849,1098,352,378]" class="Oligohymenophorea" family="Trichodinidae" genus="Trichodina" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Peritrichida" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="nobilis">
<emphasis id="B941EA8B6B7DFFD24301E37DFC484B77" box="[849,957,352,377]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">T. nobilis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFA44B686B7DFFD24394E37DFBBF4B74" author="Chen, Q. - L." box="[964,1098,352,378]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" pagination="197 - 225" refId="ref5038" refString="Chen, Q. - L. (1963) Studies on ecotoparasitic trichodinids from fresh-water fish, tadpole and crustacean in China. Acta Hydrobiologica Sinnica, 2, 197 - 225 (in Chinese with English summary)." type="journal article" year="1963">Chen, 1963</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
differs from the new species mainly in three important points: firstly, 
<taxonomicName id="4C354D1A6B7DFFD24221E395FD2B4BAF" authorityName="Chen" authorityYear="1963" box="[625,734,392,417]" class="Oligohymenophorea" family="Trichodinidae" genus="Trichodina" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Peritrichida" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="nobilis">
<emphasis id="B941EA8B6B7DFFD24221E395FD2B4BAF" box="[625,734,392,417]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">T. nobilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a large trichodinid (
<quantity id="4CCD9B7C6B7DFFD243B4E395FB9C4BAC" box="[996,1129,392,418]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.75" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="7.5" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" unit="mm" value="87.5" valueMax="100.0" valueMin="75.0">75–100µm</quantity>
), whereas the present species is medium-sized (
<quantity id="4CCD9B7C6B7DFFD241F1E3ADFDED4BC4" box="[417,536,432,458]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.3" metricValueMax="5.6" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" unit="mm" value="53.0" valueMax="56.0" valueMin="50.0">50–56µm</quantity>
); secondly, the number of denticles are different (25–26 
<emphasis id="B941EA8B6B7DFFD244ECE3ADFB2E4BC7" box="[1212,1243,432,457]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">vs.</emphasis>
26–29); thirdly, the number of degrees of turn of the adoral ciliary spiral around the peristomial disc is different (390º –400º 
<emphasis id="B941EA8B6B7DFFD240C7E01DFF434817" box="[151,182,512,537]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">vs.</emphasis>
370º–390º).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8A36996B7DFFD24097E035FB5F493C" blockId="3.[151,1436,151,818]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">
In addition, although the shapes of central part and ray in of both species are similar, the morphological difference of blade is distinct. In terms of morphology of blade, the new species has very obvious differences from 
<taxonomicName id="4C354D1A6B7DFFD2408AE065FEBF489F" authorityName="Chen" authorityYear="1963" box="[218,330,632,657]" class="Oligohymenophorea" family="Trichodinidae" genus="Trichodina" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Peritrichida" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="nobilis">
<emphasis id="B941EA8B6B7DFFD2408AE065FEBF489F" box="[218,330,632,657]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">T. nobilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The blade of 
<taxonomicName id="4C354D1A6B7DFFD24250E065FD34489F" authority="Tang &amp; Zhao &amp; Tao, 2007" authorityName="Tang &amp; Zhao &amp; Tao" authorityYear="2007" box="[512,705,632,657]" class="Oligohymenophorea" family="Trichodinidae" genus="Trichodina" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Peritrichida" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="subtilihamata" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="B941EA8B6B7DFFD24250E065FD34489F" box="[512,705,632,657]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">T. subtilihamata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A27257F06B7DFFD2429BE065FCF8489C" box="[715,781,632,658]" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is biconcave as a result of the concave anterior blade which is an S-shape. In most cases, the anterior blade surface extends Y+1 axis and apophysis of blade is prominent; whereas these structures in 
<taxonomicName id="4C354D1A6B7DFFD2420DE0D5FD3F48EF" authorityName="Chen" authorityYear="1963" box="[605,714,712,737]" class="Oligohymenophorea" family="Trichodinidae" genus="Trichodina" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Peritrichida" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="nobilis">
<emphasis id="B941EA8B6B7DFFD2420DE0D5FD3F48EF" box="[605,714,712,737]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">T. nobilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are distinctly different: the blade is fan-shaped, anterior blade surface just touches the Y+1 axis, and there is no obvious apophysis of blade. According to the comparison with the related species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C354D1A6B7DFFD241E8E105FD80493F" authorityName="Tang &amp; Zhao &amp; Tao" authorityYear="2007" box="[440,629,792,817]" class="Oligohymenophorea" family="Trichodinidae" genus="Trichodina" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Peritrichida" pageId="3" pageNumber="42" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="subtilihamata">
<emphasis id="B941EA8B6B7DFFD241E8E105FD80493F" box="[440,629,792,817]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="42">T. subtilihamata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is considered to be a new member of the genus.
</paragraph>
